But this morning to be crowded more so was the corner of Battery Park where the statue of Giovanni da Verrazzano> stands majestic: its largest bronze bust, shaped in the early 1900s by the sculptor Ettore Ximenes and placed on an elaborate granite pedestal with lateral turns. On the façade there is the sculpture of a female figure, allegory of discovery and exploration: the two life goals for Giovanni Da Verrazzano, a Florentine navigator who first, on April 17, 500 years ago, sailed with his ship the Bay of New York by sighting Staten Island, Brooklyn and Manhattan> before continuing along other lands on the Atlantic Ocean, up to Maine.
